# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: message-authentication-codes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This article provides a simple model to follow when implementing solutions to protect data at rest.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should not be stored using reversible encryption - secure password hashing algorithms should be used instead.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Password Storage Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on storing passwords.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first step in designing any application is to consider the overall architecture of the system, as this will have a huge impact on the technical implementation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This process should begin with considering the threat model of the application (i.e, who you are trying to protect that data against).
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that many cloud environments provide these services, so these should be taken advantage of where possible.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on this topic.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Which layer(s) are most appropriate will depend on the threat model.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, hardware level encryption is effective at protecting against the physical theft of the server, but will provide no protection if an attacker is able to compromise the server remotely.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The best way to protect sensitive information is to not store it in the first place.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although this applies to all kinds of information, it is most often applicable to credit card details, as they are highly desirable for attackers, and PCI DSS has such stringent requirements for how they must be stored.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, the storage of sensitive information should be avoided.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For symmetric encryption **AES** with a key that's at least **128 bits** (ideally **256 bits**) and a secure mode should be used as the preferred algorithm.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For asymmetric encryption, use elliptical curve cryptography (ECC) with a secure curve such as **Curve25519** as a preferred algorithm.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If ECC is not available and **RSA** must be used, then ensure that the key is at least **2048 bits**.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Many other symmetric and asymmetric algorithms are available which have their own pros and cons, and they may be better or worse than AES or Curve25519 in specific use cases.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases there may be regulatory requirements that limit the algorithms that can be used, such as FIPS 140-2 or PCI DSS.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are various modes that can be used to allow block ciphers (such as AES) to encrypt arbitrary amounts of data, in the same way that a stream cipher would.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These modes have different security and performance characteristics, and a full discussion of them is outside the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Some of the modes have requirements to generate secure initialisation vectors (IVs) and other attributes, but these should be handled automatically by the library.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, authenticated modes should always be used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These provide guarantees of the integrity and authenticity of the data, as well as confidentiality.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The most commonly used authenticated modes are **GCM** and **CCM**, which should be used as a first preference.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If GCM or CCM are not available, then CTR mode or CBC mode should be used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As these do not provide any guarantees about the authenticity of the data, separate authentication should be implemented, such as using the Encrypt-then-MAC technique.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] ECB should not be used outside of very specific circumstances.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For RSA, it is essential to enable Random Padding.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random Padding is also known as OAEP or Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This class of defense protects against Known Plain Text Attacks by adding randomness at the beginning of the payload.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Padding Schema of PKCS#1 is typically used in this case.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random numbers (or strings) are needed for various security critical functionality, such as generating encryption keys, IVs, session IDs, CSRF tokens or password reset tokens.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important that these are generated securely, and that it is not possible for an attacker to guess and predict them.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is generally not possible for computers to generate truly random numbers (without special hardware), so most systems and languages provide two different types of randomness.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Pseudo-Random Number Generators (PRNG) provide low-quality randomness that are much faster, and can be used for non-security related functionality (such as ordering results on a page, or randomising UI elements).
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they **must not** be used for anything security critical, as it is often possible for attackers to guess or predict the output.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Cryptographically Secure Pseudo-Random Number Generators (CSPRNG) are designed to produce a much higher quality of randomness (more strictly, a greater amount of entropy), making them safe to use for security-sensitive functionality.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they are slower and more CPU intensive, can end up blocking in some circumstances when large amounts of random data are requested.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, if large amounts of non-security related randomness are needed, they may not be appropriate.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The table below shows the recommended algorithms for each language, as well as insecure functions that should not be used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Universally unique identifiers (UUIDs or GUIDs) are sometimes used as a quick way to generate random strings.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although they can provide a reasonable source of randomness, this will depend on the type or version of the UUID that is created.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Specifically, version 1 UUIDs are comprised of a high precision timestamp and the MAC address of the system that generated them, so are **not random** (although they may be hard to guess, given the timestamp is to the nearest 100ns).
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Type 4 UUIDs are randomly generated, although whether this is done using a CSPRNG will depend on the implementation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Unless this is known to be secure in the specific language or framework, the randomness of UUIDs should not be relied upon.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Applications should be designed to still be secure even if cryptographic controls fail.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Any information that is stored in an encrypted form should also be protected by additional layers of security.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Application should also not rely on the security of encrypted URL parameters, and should enforce strong access control to prevent unauthorised access to information.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys should be randomly generated using a cryptographically secure function, such as those discussed in the Secure Random Number Generation section.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys **should not** be based on common words or phrases, or on "random" characters generated by mashing the keyboard.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where multiple keys are used (such as data separate data-encrypting and key-encrypting keys), they should be fully independent from each other.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Once one of these criteria have been met, a new key should be generated and used for encrypting any new data.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Marking each item with the ID of the key that was used to encrypt it, and storing multiple keys to allow the old data to be decrypted.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first option should generally be preferred, as it greatly simplifies both the application code and key management processes; however, it may not always be feasible.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that old keys should generally be stored for a certain period after they have been retired, in case old backups of copies of the data need to be decrypted.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is important that the code and processes required to rotate a key are in place **before** they are required, so that keys can be quickly rotated in the event of a compromise.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Additionally, processes should also be implemented to allow the encryption algorithm or library to be changed, in case a new vulnerability is found in the algorithm or implementation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Securely storing cryptographic keys is one of the hardest problems to solve, as the application always needs to have some level of access to the keys in order to decrypt the data.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] While it may not be possible to fully protect the keys from an attacker who has fully compromised the application, a number of steps can be taken to make it harder for them to obtain the keys.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, the secure storage mechanisms provided by the operating system, framework or cloud service provider should be used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are many advantages to using these types of secure storage over simply putting keys in configuration files.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases none of these will be available, such as in a shared hosting environment, meaning that it is not possible to obtain a high degree of protection for any encryption keys.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet provides more details on securely storing secrets.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should be stored in a separate location from encrypted data.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the data is stored in a database, the keys should be stored in the filesystem.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that if an attacker only has access to one of these (for example through directory traversal or SQL injection), they cannot access both the keys and the data.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the architecture of the environment, it may be possible to store the keys and data on separate systems, which would provide a greater degree of isolation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should themselves be stored in an encrypted form.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For this to be effective, the KEK must be stored separately from the DEK.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The encrypted DEK can be stored with the data, but will only be usable if an attacker is able to also obtain the KEK, which is stored on another system.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The KEK should also be at least as strong as the DEK.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The envelope encryption guidance from Google contains further details on how to manage DEKs and KEKs.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In simpler application architectures (such as shared hosting environments) where the KEK and DEK cannot be stored separately, there is limited value to this approach, as an attacker is likely to be able to obtain both of the keys at the same time.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, it can provide an additional barrier to unskilled attackers.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] A key derivation function (KDF) could be used to generate a KEK from user-supplied input (such a passphrase), which would then be used to encrypt a randomly generated DEK.
[src:message-authentication-codes/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This allows the KEK to be easily changed (when the user changes their passphrase), without needing to re-encrypt the data (as the DEK remains the same).
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In cryptography, an **HMAC** (sometimes expanded as either **keyed-hash message authentication code** or **hash-based message authentication code**) is a specific type of message authentication code (MAC) involving a cryptographic hash function and a secret cryptographic key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] As with any MAC, it may be used to simultaneously verify both the data integrity and authenticity of a message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] An HMAC is a type of keyed hash function that can also be used in a key derivation scheme or a key stretching scheme.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] HMAC can provide authentication using a shared secret instead of using digital signatures with asymmetric cryptography.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] It trades off the need for a complex public key infrastructure by delegating the key exchange to the communicating parties, who are responsible for establishing and using a trusted channel to agree on the key prior to communication.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Any cryptographic hash function, such as SHA-2 or SHA-3, may be used in the calculation of an HMAC; the resulting MAC algorithm is termed HMAC-*x*, where *x* is the hash function used (e.g.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The cryptographic strength of the HMAC depends upon the cryptographic strength of the underlying hash function, the size of its hash output, and the size and quality of the key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] HMAC uses two passes of hash computation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Before either pass, the secret key is used to derive two keys – inner and outer.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Next, the first pass of the hash algorithm produces an internal hash derived from the message and the inner key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The second pass produces the final HMAC code derived from the inner hash result and the outer key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Thus the algorithm provides better immunity against length extension attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] An iterative hash function (one that uses the Merkle–Damgård construction) breaks up a message into blocks of a fixed size and iterates over them with a compression function.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] For example, SHA-256 operates on 512-bit blocks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The size of the output of HMAC is the same as that of the underlying hash function (e.g., 256 and 512 bits in the case of SHA-256 and SHA3-512, respectively), although it can be truncated if desired.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Instead, the message (encrypted or not) must be sent alongside the HMAC hash.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Parties with the secret key will hash the message again themselves, and if it is authentic, the received and computed hashes will match.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The definition and analysis of the HMAC construction was first published in 1996 in a paper by Mihir Bellare, Ran Canetti, and Hugo Krawczyk, and they also wrote RFC 2104 in 1997.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The 1996 paper also defined a nested variant called NMAC (Nested MAC).
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] FIPS PUB 198 generalizes and standardizes the use of HMACs.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] HMAC is used within the IPsec, SSH and TLS protocols and for JSON Web Tokens.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] ; either by padding to the right with 0s up to the block size, or by hashing down to less than or equal to the block size first and then padding to the right with zeros.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] is the block-sized outer padding, consisting of repeated bytes valued 0x5c.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] is the block-sized inner padding, consisting of repeated bytes valued 0x36.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The following pseudocode demonstrates how HMAC may be implemented.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The block size is 512 bits (64 bytes) when using one of the following hash functions: SHA-1, MD5, RIPEMD-128.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The design of the HMAC specification was motivated by the existence of attacks on more trivial mechanisms for combining a key with a hash function.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] For example, one might assume the same security that HMAC provides could be achieved with MAC = **H**(*key* ∥ *message*).
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] However, this method suffers from a serious flaw: with most hash functions, it is easy to append data to the message without knowing the key and obtain another valid MAC ("length-extension attack").
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Using MAC = **H**(*key* ∥ *message* ∥ *key*) is better, but various security papers have suggested vulnerabilities with this approach, even when two different keys are used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] No known extension attacks have been found against the current HMAC specification which is defined as **H**(*key* ∥ **H**(*key* ∥ *message*)) because the outer application of the hash function masks the intermediate result of the internal hash.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The values of *ipad* and *opad* are not critical to the security of the algorithm, but were defined in such a way to have a large Hamming distance from each other and so the inner and outer keys will have fewer bits in common.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The security reduction of HMAC does require them to be different in at least one bit.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The Keccak hash function, that was selected by NIST as the SHA-3 competition winner, does not need this nested approach and can be used to generate a MAC by simply prepending the key to the message, as it is not susceptible to length-extension attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The cryptographic strength of the HMAC depends upon the size of the secret key that is used and the security of the underlying hash function used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] It has been proven that the security of an HMAC construction is directly related to security properties of the hash function used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] The most common attack against HMACs is brute force to uncover the secret key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] HMACs are substantially less affected by collisions than their underlying hashing algorithms alone.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In particular, Mihir Bellare proved that HMAC is a pseudo-random function (PRF) under the sole assumption that the compression function is a PRF.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Therefore, HMAC-MD5 does not suffer from the same weaknesses that have been found in MD5.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] RFC 2104 requires that "keys longer than *B* bytes are first hashed using *H*" which leads to a confusing pseudo-collision: if the key is longer than the hash block size (e.g.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] 64 bytes for SHA-1), then `HMAC(k, m)` is computed as `HMAC(H(k), m)`.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] This property is sometimes raised as a possible weakness of HMAC in password-hashing scenarios: it has been demonstrated that it's possible to find a long ASCII string and a random value whose hash will be also an ASCII string, and both values will produce the same HMAC output.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In 2006, Jongsung Kim, Alex Biryukov, Bart Preneel, and Seokhie Hong showed how to distinguish HMAC with reduced versions of MD5 and SHA-1 or full versions of HAVAL, MD4, and SHA-0 from a random function or HMAC with a random function.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Differential distinguishers allow an attacker to devise a forgery attack on HMAC.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] Furthermore, differential and rectangle distinguishers can lead to second-preimage attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] HMAC with the full version of MD4 can be forged with this knowledge.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] These attacks do not contradict the security proof of HMAC, but provide insight into HMAC based on existing cryptographic hash functions.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In 2009, Xiaoyun Wang *et al.* presented a distinguishing attack on HMAC-MD5 without using related keys.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] It can distinguish an instantiation of HMAC with MD5 from an instantiation with a random function with 297 queries with probability 0.87.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In 2011 an informational RFC 6151 was published to summarize security considerations in MD5 and HMAC-MD5.
[src:message-authentication-codes/hmac] In May 2011, RFC 6234 was published detailing the abstract theory and source code for SHA-based HMACs.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] Algorithms like MD5, SHA-1 and most of SHA-2 that are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction are susceptible to this kind of attack.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] Truncated versions of SHA-2, including SHA-384 and SHA-512/256 are not susceptible, nor is the SHA-3 algorithm.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] HMAC also uses a different construction and so is not vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] A secret suffix MAC, which is calculated as **Hash**(*message* ‖ *secret*), isn't vulnerable to a length extension attack, but is vulnerable to another attack based on a hash collision.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The vulnerable hashing functions work by taking the input message, and using it to transform an internal state.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] After all of the input has been processed, the hash digest is generated by outputting the internal state of the function.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] It is possible to reconstruct the internal state from the hash digest, which can then be used to process the new data.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] In this way, one may extend the message and compute the hash that is a valid signature for the new message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The server would perform the request given (to deliver ten waffles of type eggo to the given location for user "1") only if the signature is valid for the user.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The signature used here is a MAC, signed with a key not known to the attacker.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] It is possible for an attacker to modify the request in this example by switching the requested waffle from "eggo" to "liege." This can be done by taking advantage of a flexibility in the message format if duplicate content in the query string gives preference to the latter value.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] This flexibility does not indicate an exploit in the message format, because the message format was never designed to be cryptographically secure in the first place, without the signature algorithm to help it.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] In order to sign this new message, typically the attacker would need to know the key the message was signed with, and generate a new signature by generating a new MAC.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] However, with a length extension attack, it is possible to feed the hash (the signature given above) into the state of the hashing function, and continue where the original request had left off, so long as the length of the original request is known.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] In this request, the original key's length was 14 bytes, which could be determined by trying forged requests with various assumed lengths, and checking which length results in a request that the server accepts as valid.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The message as fed into the hashing function is often padded, as many algorithms can only work on input messages whose lengths are a multiple of some given size.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The content of this padding is always specified by the hash function used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The attacker must include all of these padding bits in their forged message before the internal states of their message and the original will line up.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] The attacker knows that the state behind the hashed key/message pair for the original message is identical to that of new message up to the final "&." The attacker also knows the hash digest at this point, which means they know the internal state of the hashing function at that point.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] It is then trivial to initialize a hashing algorithm at that point, input the last few characters, and generate a new digest which can sign his new message without the original key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/length-extension-attack] By combining the new signature and new data into a new request, the server will see the forged request as a valid request due to the signature being the same as it would have been generated if the password was known.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] In cryptography, a **message authentication code** (**MAC**), sometimes known as an **authentication tag**, is a short piece of information used for authenticating and integrity-checking a message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] In other words, it is used to confirm that the message came from the stated sender (its authenticity) and has not been changed (its integrity).
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The MAC value allows verifiers (who also possess a secret key) to detect any changes to the message content.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The term **message integrity code** (**MIC**) is frequently substituted for the term *MAC*, especially in communications to distinguish it from the use of the latter as *Media Access Control* (as in *MAC address*).
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] However, some authors use MIC to refer to a message digest, which aims only to uniquely but opaquely identify a single message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] As such, it is recommended to avoid the term *message integrity code* (MIC), and instead use *checksum*, *error detection code*, *hash*, **keyed hash**, *message authentication code*, or *protected checksum*.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] A secure message authentication code must resist attempts by an adversary to forge tags, for arbitrary, selected, or all messages, including under conditions of known- or chosen-message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] It should be computationally infeasible to compute a valid tag of the given message without knowledge of the key, even if for the worst case, we assume the adversary knows the tag of any message but the one in question.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] where *A**S*(*k*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle *S*(*k*, · ), and Query(*A**S*(*k*, · ), 1*n*) denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows *n*.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Clearly we require that any adversary cannot directly query the string *x* on *S*, since otherwise a valid tag can be easily obtained by that adversary.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] While MAC functions are similar to cryptographic hash functions, they possess different security requirements.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] To be considered secure, a MAC function must resist existential forgery under chosen-message attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] This means that even if an attacker has access to an oracle which possesses the secret key and generates MACs for messages of the attacker's choosing, the attacker cannot guess the MAC for other messages (which were not used to query the oracle) without performing infeasible amounts of computation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] MACs differ from digital signatures as MAC values are both generated and verified using the same secret key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] This implies that the sender and receiver of a message must agree on the same key before initiating communications, as is the case with symmetric encryption.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] For the same reason, MACs do not provide the property of non-repudiation offered by signatures specifically in the case of a network-wide shared secret key: any user who can verify a MAC is also capable of generating MACs for other messages.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] In contrast, a digital signature is generated using the private key of a key pair, which is public-key cryptography.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Since this private key is only accessible to its holder, a digital signature proves that a document was signed by none other than that holder.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Thus, digital signatures do offer non-repudiation.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] This is commonly done in the finance industry.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] While the primary goal of a MAC is to prevent forgery by adversaries without knowledge of the secret key, this is insufficient in certain scenarios.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] When an adversary is able to control the MAC key, stronger guarantees are needed, akin to collision resistance or preimage security in hash functions.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] For MACs, these concepts are known as *commitment* and *context-discovery* security.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] MAC algorithms can be constructed from other cryptographic primitives, like cryptographic hash functions (as in the case of HMAC) or from block cipher algorithms (OMAC, CCM, GCM, and PMAC).
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] However many of the fastest MAC algorithms, like UMAC-VMAC and Poly1305-AES, are constructed based on universal hashing.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Intrinsically keyed hash algorithms such as SipHash are also by definition MACs; they can be even faster than universal-hashing based MACs.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Additionally, the MAC algorithm can deliberately combine two or more cryptographic primitives, so as to maintain protection even if one of them is later found to be vulnerable.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] For instance, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) versions before 1.2, the input data is split in halves that are each processed with a different hashing primitive (SHA-1 and SHA-2) then XORed together to output the MAC.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Universal hashing and in particular pairwise independent hash functions provide a secure message authentication code as long as the key is used at most once.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] This can be seen as the one-time pad for authentication.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The simplest such pairwise independent hash function is defined by the random key, *key* = (*a*, *b*), and the MAC tag for a message *m* is computed as *tag* = (*am* + *b*) mod *p*, where *p* is prime.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] More generally, *k*-independent hashing functions provide a secure message authentication code as long as the key is used less than *k* times for *k*-ways independent hashing functions.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Message authentication codes and data origin authentication have been also discussed in the framework of quantum cryptography.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] By contrast to other cryptographic tasks, such as key distribution, for a rather broad class of quantum MACs it has been shown that quantum resources do not offer any advantage over unconditionally secure one-time classical MACs.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Various standards exist that define MAC algorithms.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] ISO/IEC 9797-1 and -2 define generic models and algorithms that can be used with any block cipher or hash function, and a variety of different parameters.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] These models and parameters allow more specific algorithms to be defined by nominating the parameters.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] For example, the FIPS PUB 113 algorithm is functionally equivalent to ISO/IEC 9797-1 MAC algorithm 1 with padding method 1 and a block cipher algorithm of DES.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] In this example, the sender of a message runs it through a MAC algorithm to produce a MAC data tag.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The message and the MAC tag are then sent to the receiver.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The receiver in turn runs the message portion of the transmission through the same MAC algorithm using the same key, producing a second MAC data tag.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] The receiver then compares the first MAC tag received in the transmission to the second generated MAC tag.
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] If they are identical, the receiver can safely assume that the message was not altered or tampered with during transmission (data integrity).
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] However, to allow the receiver to be able to detect replay attacks, the message itself must contain data that assures that this same message can only be sent once (e.g. time stamp, sequence number or use of a one-time MAC).
[src:message-authentication-codes/message-authentication-code] Otherwise an attacker could – without even understanding its content – record this message and play it back at a later time, producing the same result as the original sender.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Originally Poly1305 was proposed as part of Poly1305-AES, a Carter–Wegman authenticator that combines the Poly1305 hash with AES-128 to authenticate many messages using a single short key and distinct message numbers.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Poly1305 was later applied with a single-use key generated for each message using XSalsa20 in the NaCl crypto_secretbox_xsalsa20poly1305 authenticated cipher, and then using ChaCha in the ChaCha20-Poly1305 authenticated cipher deployed in TLS on the internet.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Poly1305 takes a 16-byte secret key r and an L -byte message m and returns a 16-byte hash $\operatorname {Poly1305} _{r}(m)$ .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Interprets the 16-byte chunks as 17-byte little-endian integers by appending a 1 byte to every 16-byte chunk, to be used as coefficients of a polynomial.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Evaluates the polynomial at the point r modulo the prime $2^{130}-5$ .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Reduces the result modulo $2^{128}$ encoded in little-endian return a 16-byte hash.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Thus there are $2^{106}$ distinct possible values of r .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] is called the **authenticator** for the message m .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] If a sender and recipient share the 32-byte secret key $(r,s)$ in advance, chosen uniformly at random, then the sender can transmit an authenticated message $(a,m)$ .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] However, the same key $(r,s)$ must not be reused for two messages.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] and find a root of the resulting polynomial to recover a small list of candidates for the secret evaluation point r , and from that the secret pad s .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] The adversary can then use this to forge additional messages with high probability.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Poly1305-AES uses AES-128 to generate $p_{i}:=\operatorname {AES} _{k}(i)$ , where i is encoded as a 16-byte little-endian integer.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Specifically, a Poly1305-AES key is a 32-byte pair $(r,k)$ of a 16-byte evaluation point r , as above, and a 16-byte AES key k .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] where 16-byte strings and integers are identified by little-endian encoding.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Without knowledge of $(r,k)$ , the adversary has low probability of forging any authenticated messages that the recipient will accept as genuine.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Suppose the adversary sees C authenticated messages and attempts D forgeries, and can distinguish $\operatorname {AES} _{k}$ from a uniform random permutation with advantage at most $\delta$ .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] The message number i must never be repeated with the same key $(r,k)$ .
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] If it is, the adversary can recover a small list of candidates for r and $\operatorname {AES} _{k}(i)$ , as with the one-time authenticator, and use that to forge messages.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] The NaCl `crypto_secretbox_xsalsa20poly1305` authenticated cipher uses a message number i with the XSalsa20 stream cipher to generate a per-message key stream, the first 32 bytes of which are taken as a one-time Poly1305 key $(r_{i},s_{i})$ and the rest of which is used for encrypting the message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] It then uses Poly1305 as a one-time authenticator for the ciphertext of the message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] ChaCha20-Poly1305 uses the first 32 bytes of the ChaCha stream cipher output to generate a one-time Poly1305 key, discards the next 32 bytes, and uses the rest to encrypt the message.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] XChaCha20-Poly1305 using XChaCha instead of ChaCha or XSalsa20 has also been described.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] where r is a uniform random Poly1305 key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Here arithmetic inside the $\Pr[\cdots ]$ is taken to be in $\mathbb {Z} /2^{128}\mathbb {Z}$ for simplicity.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] The security of Poly1305-AES against forgery follows from the Carter–Wegman–Shoup structure, which instantiates a Carter–Wegman authenticator with a permutation to generate the per-message pad.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] Poly1305-AES can be computed at high speed in various CPUs: for an *n*-byte message, no more than 3.1*n* + 780 Athlon cycles are needed, for example.
[src:message-authentication-codes/poly1305] The author has released optimized source code for Athlon, Pentium Pro/II/III/M, PowerPC, and UltraSPARC, in addition to non-optimized reference implementations in C and C++ as public domain software.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] In cryptography, a **timing attack** is a side-channel attack in which the attacker attempts to compromise a cryptosystem by analyzing the time taken to execute cryptographic algorithms.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Every logical operation in a computer takes time to execute, and the time can differ based on the input; with precise measurements of the time for each operation, an attacker may be able to work backwards to the input.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Information can leak from a system through measurement of the time it takes to respond to certain queries.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] How much this information can help an attacker depends on many variables such as cryptographic system design, the CPU running the system, the algorithms used, assorted implementation details, timing attack countermeasures, and accuracy of the timing measurements.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Any algorithm that has data-dependent timing variation is vulnerable to timing attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Removing timing-dependencies is difficult since varied execution time can occur at any level.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Vulnerability to timing attacks is often overlooked in the design phase and can be introduced unintentionally with compiler optimizations.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Countermeasures include blinding and constant-time functions.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Many cryptographic algorithms can be implemented (or masked by a proxy) in a way that reduces or eliminates data-dependent timing information, known as a **constant-time algorithm**.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] A trivial "**timing-safe implementation"** can be found here.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Imagine an implementation in which every call to a subroutine always returns exactly after time *T* has elapsed, where *T* is the maximum time it takes to execute that routine on every possible authorized input.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Such a hypothetical implementation would leak no information about the data supplied to that invocation (in reality, non-data-dependent timing variations are unavoidable).
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The downside of such an approach is that the time used for all executions becomes that of the worst-case performance of the function.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] It would appear that blinding should be applied to avoid vulnerability to timing attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The execution time for the square-and-multiply algorithm used in modular exponentiation depends linearly on the number of '1' bits in the key.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] While the number of '1' bits alone is not nearly enough information to make finding the key easy, repeated executions with the same key and different inputs can be used to perform statistical correlation analysis of timing information to recover the key completely, even by a passive attacker.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Observed timing measurements often include noise (from such sources as network latency, or disk drive access differences from access to access, and the error correction techniques used to recover from transmission errors).
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Nevertheless, timing attacks are practical against a number of encryption algorithms, including RSA, ElGamal, and the Digital Signature Algorithm.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] In 2003, Boneh and Brumley demonstrated a practical network-based timing attack on SSL-enabled web servers, based on a different vulnerability having to do with the use of RSA with Chinese remainder theorem optimizations.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The actual network distance was small in their experiments, but the attack successfully recovered a server private key in a matter of hours.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] This demonstration led to the widespread deployment and use of blinding techniques in SSL implementations.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] In this context, blinding is intended to remove correlations between key and encryption time.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Some versions of Unix use a relatively expensive implementation of the *crypt* library function for hashing an 8-character password into an 11-character string.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] On older hardware, this computation took a deliberately and measurably long time: as much as two or three seconds in some cases.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The *login* program in early versions of Unix executed the crypt function only when the login name was recognized by the system.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] This leaked information through timing about the validity of the login name, even when the password was incorrect.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] An attacker could exploit such leaks by first applying brute-force to produce a list of login names known to be valid, then attempt to gain access by combining only these names with a large set of passwords known to be frequently used.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Without any information on the validity of login names the time needed to execute such an approach would increase by orders of magnitude, effectively rendering it useless.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Later versions of Unix have fixed this leak by always executing the crypt function, regardless of login name validity.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] Two otherwise securely isolated processes running on a single system with either cache memory or virtual memory can communicate by deliberately causing page faults and/or cache misses in one process, then monitoring the resulting changes in access times from the other.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The 2017 Meltdown and Spectre attacks which forced CPU manufacturers (including Intel, AMD, ARM, and IBM) to redesign their CPUs both rely on timing attacks.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] As of early 2018, almost every computer system in the world is affected by Spectre.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] In 2018, many internet servers were still vulnerable to slight variations of the original timing attack on RSA, two decades after the original vulnerability was discovered.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] The following C code demonstrates a typical insecure string comparison which stops testing as soon as a character doesn't match.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] In the world of C library functions, the first function is analogous to `memcmp()`, while the latter is analogous to NetBSD's `consttime_memequal()` or OpenBSD's `timingsafe_bcmp()` and `timingsafe_memcmp`.
[src:message-authentication-codes/timing-attack] On other systems, the comparison function from cryptographic libraries like OpenSSL and libsodium can be used.
